Here's a complete example. I'll walk through each piece.

---

### 1. Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user profile by ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("List all posts for a given user.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUserPosts(
        [Description("The numeric user ID whose posts to retrieve")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}/posts", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = false, Idempotent = false),
     Description("Create a new post for a user.")]
    public async Task<string> CreatePost(
        [Description("The user ID who is authoring the post")] int userId,
        [Description("The post title")] string title,
        [Description("The post body text")] string body,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = new { userId, title, body };
        var response = await httpClient.PostAsJsonAsync("/posts", payload, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

### 2. `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr so stdout stays clean for JSON-RPC
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Register HttpClient with a base address for the API
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer(options =>
{
    options.ServerInfo = new() { Name = "ApiServer", Version = "1.0.0" };
})
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

### 3. How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK uses two injection styles, and in both cases **injected services are invisible to the LLM** — they never appear in the tool's JSON schema.

| Style | How it works |
|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is resolved from the DI container each invocation. Services go in the primary constructor (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own services). |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services can appear directly as method parameters. The SDK sees they're registered in DI and injects them instead of exposing them in the schema. |

**What the SDK auto-injects** (no registration needed):

- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — access to the server instance
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — report progress to client

**What you register yourself** in `Program.cs`:

- `AddHttpClient<T>()` — typed `HttpClient`
- `AddSingleton<IMyService, MyService>()` — your own services
- `ILogger<T>` — already registered by the host builder

The constructor injection style (shown above) is preferred when tools share services, since it keeps method signatures clean — only LLM-facing parameters appear on each method.
